### PR #128: operator validation expansion plan

5-phase plan covering activations + SFU modeling (Phase 1), element-wise
matrix (Phase 2), softmax with composite-op infrastructure (Phase 3),
LayerNorm + RMSNorm (Phase 4), attention head as decomposed graph
(Phase 5). Total scope ~3-6 weeks.

Phase 5 framing per user direction: attention head IS a computational graph
of operators we already model -- linear / matmul / element-wise scale /
softmax. Decomposition-first, no fusion. Justified because the
compiler/runtime layer is still under development; PyTorch eager attention
IS the unfused decomposition; when fused kernels do land, measured-fused
vs predicted-unfused = the fusion uplift, an architecturally meaningful
prioritization signal for compiler/runtime work.

5 GitHub issues filed for tracking: #123-#127 (one per phase) with explicit
dependencies (Phase 4 / 5 block on Phase 3's composite-op infrastructure).

## Key decisions

1. **PR #117 ships even though V4 PASS doesn't move.** Memory-physics
   correctness still matters for downstream consumers; latency precision
   gains will translate to PASS gains when the regime classifier is also
   fixed.
2. **PR #118 linear scale = 0.94 not 0.85.** Pareto choice constrained by
   the legacy-path energy floor; tier-aware path can use 0.85 once
   `RunnerConfig` defaults are updated to match V5-3b production.
3. **PR #119 measurement-priority over analytical-classifier improvement.**
   Tried OI-aware analytical classifier first -- caused i7 V4 PASS to
   regress 17 -> 5 because tighter ALU_BOUND tolerance (10% vs 25%
   DRAM_BOUND) failed records that previously passed. Measurement-priority
   only relabels concrete-measurement shapes, leaves AMBIGUOUS untouched.
4. **PR #120 KPU T64 uses fp16 not bf16 for default comparison.** KPU's
   bf16 fabric also delivers fp16 at 33 TFLOPS, so fp16 gives apples-to-
   apples comparison with Orin Nano. `--dtype-for kpu_t64=bf16` available
   for explicit bf16 runs.
5. **Phase 5 (attention head) framed as decomposition-first.** Realistic
   first-order baseline matching PyTorch eager; quantifies the fusion gap
   when fused kernels land.

